    <!-- What Are Corrugated Sheets -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">What Are Corrugated Cardboard Sheets?</h2>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Corrugated cardboard sheets are panels made of kraft paper and fluted corrugated material. The characteristic wave or flute pattern creates air pockets that provide cushioning, strength, and rigidity while minimizing weight. This design has made corrugated cardboard the world's most widely used packaging material for protective shipping and internal packaging applications.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">Basic Structure</h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        A corrugated sheet typically consists of an outer kraft paper layer (called liners), a middle fluted layer, and potentially additional reinforcing layers for double-wall construction. The fluted middle layer creates the corrugated structure, while the kraft paper liners provide flat surface protection. This layered construction ensures durability while keeping weight and cost reasonable.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">Why Industries Choose Corrugated Sheets</h3>
      <ul class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4 space-y-2 list-disc list-inside">
        <li>Excellent cushioning for fragile items during shipping and handling</li>
        <li>Lightweight design reduces shipping weight and costs</li>
        <li>Recyclable and environmentally friendly material</li>
        <li>Cost-effective compared to foam, plastic, or other protective materials</li>
        <li>Versatile for multiple applications from dividers to protective backing</li>
        <li>Easy to cut and customize for specific product shapes and sizes</li>
        <li>Moisture resistance in protective applications</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- Types and Flute Grades -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">Understanding Corrugated Sheet Types: Flute Grades Explained</h2>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        The "flute" refers to the wave pattern in the middle layer of corrugated sheets. Different flute sizes and configurations offer varying levels of protection, weight, and rigidity. Understanding flute grades helps you select the optimal sheets for your specific products.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">A-Flute: Maximum Strength</h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        A-flute features the largest wave pattern (approximately 4.8mm) creating maximum crush strength and stiffness. Use A-flute for heavy items, machinery parts, automotive components, and applications requiring maximum structural support. While it uses more material, the superior strength justifies the cost for heavy-duty applications. Ideal for internal bracing and support structures within boxes.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">C-Flute: Balanced Protection</h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        C-flute waves measure approximately 3.2mm, balancing protection with material efficiency. This is the most commonly used flute grade for general packaging applications including dividers, protective layers, and cushioning for moderately fragile items. C-flute offers excellent value for most business requirements and works well with standard sized boxes.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">B-Flute: Compact Strength</h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        B-flute waves are smaller at approximately 2.4mm, providing significant strength in a more compact profile. When space inside boxes is limited but protection is important, B-flute offers the right balance. This grade works especially well for products with defined shapes where space efficiency matters, such as electronics or glassware.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">E-Flute and F-Flute: Lightweight Options</h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        E-flute (1.6mm) and F-flute (0.8mm) are micro-flutes providing minimal cushioning in the thinnest profile. These are used when weight is critical, such as for lightweight items, or when space constraints are extreme. E-flute and F-flute are less common in general packaging but essential for specific high-volume, lightweight applications.
      </p>

      <div class="bg-surface-variant/50 border border-outline-variant/20 rounded-2xl p-6 my-8">
        <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-4">Quick Flute Selection Guide</h3>
        <ul class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4 space-y-2 list-disc list-inside">
          <li><strong>Heavy/Sturdy Items:</strong> A-flute or double-wall sheets</li>
          <li><strong>General Purpose Protection:</strong> C-flute (most common choice)</li>
          <li><strong>Space-Constrained Applications:</strong> B-flute or E-flute</li>
          <li><strong>Lightweight Items:</strong> E-flute or F-flute</li>
          <li><strong>Fragile/Valuable Products:</strong> Double-wall C-flute or A-flute</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Uses in Packaging -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">Uses of Corrugated Cardboard Sheets in Packaging</h2>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Corrugated sheets are incredibly versatile. Understanding their various applications helps you optimize your packaging operations and ensure products arrive safely.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">Internal Dividers and Separators</h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        One of the most common uses is creating dividers within shipping boxes. For example, a box containing 12 glass mugs might use corrugated sheets to create separate compartments, preventing items from touching and breaking during transit. Similarly, electronics businesses use dividers to separate sensitive components and cushion internal elements. Custom-cut dividers maximize space while ensuring product safety.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">Protective Cushioning Layers</h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Layering corrugated sheets at the bottom, sides, and top of boxes creates protective cushioning for fragile items. The fluted structure absorbs impact energy, reducing shock to products inside. This is critical for ceramics, glassware, furniture, and any items prone to damage from drops or rough handling during shipping.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">Custom Protective Packaging</h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Corrugated sheets can be cut and formed into custom protective solutions for uniquely shaped products. Furniture makers might create custom supports and bracing. Electronics manufacturers might form protective sleeves or corner guards. The material's workability makes it ideal for creating one-of-a-kind protective solutions without expensive custom manufacturing.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">Protective Backing and Stiffening</h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Adding corrugated sheets to the back of boxes increases stiffness and prevents box collapse under pressure. This is especially important for heavy items stacked during storage or transportation. The added rigidity ensures boxes maintain integrity throughout the supply chain.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">Template and Pattern Creation</h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Businesses use corrugated sheets to create custom packaging templates for one-time or limited-run products. Test packaging configurations with corrugated sheets before committing to larger manufacturing orders, saving development costs and time.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Industries Using Corrugated Sheets -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">Industries That Rely on Corrugated Cardboard Sheets</h2>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">Electronics and Technology</h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Electronics manufacturers use corrugated sheets extensively to protect sensitive components, circuit boards, and fragile assemblies. Custom dividers prevent component movement, and protective layers cushion impact during the rough handling that occurs throughout shipping networks.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">Furniture Manufacturing</h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Furniture companies rely on corrugated sheets for corner protection, edge guards, and internal bracing. Protecting finished furniture during shipping preserves aesthetic quality and prevents costly damage claims from customers receiving scratched or broken items.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">Ceramics and Glassware</h3>
